article.description: Rachel Allison scored 18 points and Jessica Morrow added 13 off the bench to lead No. 10 Baylor over St. John's, 75-65 on Saturday night.
article.headline: No. 10 Baylor seizes control early to hold off St. John's
article.linkText: Baylor hands St. John's its first loss of season
article.story:
WACO, Texas --  Jessica Morrow didn't start for the first time this season for Baylor, but that didn't faze her.

Rachel Allison scored 18 points and Morrow added 13 off the bench to lead the No. 10 Bears over St. John's, 75-65 on Saturday night.

Morrow was replaced in the Baylor lineup by Kelli Griffin for the first time this season, but responded with her fifth double-digit scoring performance. Griffin finished with a career-high seven assists.

"Whatever coach decides, she's smart," Morrow said. "She knows what's best for the team, and I want what's best for the team, too. ... I just want to win."

Baylor coach Kim Mulkey started two ball-handlers in Jhasmin Player and Griffin to counter St. John's full-court press, which still managed to force 16 turnovers.

Baylor went on a 9-0 run early in the first half to take a 10-point lead and seize control. A 7-0 run later in the first half put Baylor up 12. The Red Storm wouldn't come within 10 points of the Lady Bears the rest of the game.

The Red Storm shot 66 percent in the second half and were able to narrow a 24-point deficit in the final 10 minutes. But foul trouble for leading scorer Monique Mclean and others kept the Red Storm from mounting a serious charge.

Still, Mulkey seemed irritated that St. John's made it a game at the end.

"There were too many players on the floor for us not finishing out the game," Mulkey said. "It's disappointing, basically, to leave an arena when it was a 20-point game pretty much the whole night and you look at the score and it's a 10-point game."

Danielle Wilson scored 12 points for Baylor (7-1), including 10 in the first half, as the Lady Bears handed St. John's (7-1) its first loss of the season.

McLean led the Red Storm with 16 points and eight rebounds. Sky Lindsay had 11 points.

"They're a great team, great program, and a great coach, and we were happy to come in here and battle with them," St. John's coach Kim Barnes Arico said. "They caught us off-guard at the beginning of the game, but I was happy with the way we battled back and didn't quit in the second half."

Baylor was coming off its first loss of the season, a one-point defeat to Wisconsin. The Lady Bears have not lost more than one non-conference game in a single season since Mulkey took over in 2000.

The start was delayed 15 minutes because of a power outage at the Ferrell Center.
